keshire, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Kastel","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Bernhard.","German: topographic name for someone living near a castle or fort, from <i>Kastell</i> ‘fort, citadel’ (from Latin <i>castellum</i>), or a habitational name from any of numerous places in Germany so named (more usually <i>Kastell</i>).","Dutch (<b>Van Kastel</b>): same as 1 above, or a variant of <b>Van Gastel</b>, a habitational name for someone from Gastel in North Brabant."],"variants":[{"name":"Kastelic","meanings":["Slovenian: variant of <b>Kostevc</b>, a habitational name denoting someone from the Kostelsko region in Lower Carniola, named after the castle of Kostel. The surname <i>Kastelic</i> may in some cases also be a topographic name for someone who lived in or near a castle or a fort, <i>kastel</i>. Compare   Kostelec  ."]}]},{"name":"Mabel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a nickname from the Old French vocabulary word <i>amabel</i>, <i>amable</i> ‘lovely’ (akin to modern English <i>amiable</i> ‘friendly, good-humoured’). The initial vowel began to be lost as early as the 12th century (the same woman is referred to as both <i>Mabilia</i> and <i>Amabilia</i> in a document of  1185 ), but a short vowel in the resulting first syllable was standard, giving a rhyme with <i>babble</i>, until the 19th century, when people began to pronounce the name to rhyme with <i>table</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Mabel Kastel was born in 1280, in Pembrokeshire, Wales, United Kingdom, her father, Sir William Kastel   -AKA Castell, was 31 and her mother, Mrs. William Kastel, was 25. She married Stephan Parriet about 1305, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 2 daughters."},"et":{"1280–":"1280–Surnud","1280–Fem